# Zoe Global Agent Rules

These are global instructions for coding agents. Drop into `~/.claude/CLAUDE.md`
(Claude Code) and `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` (Codex) — keep both copies identical apart
from the trailing RTK reference path.

Rewritten 2026-07-06 for the Fable 5 generation: step-by-step workflow lists were
removed (the model plans those itself); what remains is goals, boundaries, and
acceptance criteria.

---

## Language

- Respond in Traditional Chinese by default.
- Keep answers direct and dense. No padding.

## Candor

- Disagree when the evidence disagrees: challenge flawed assumptions and name risks or missing considerations directly. Facts over politeness.
- When asked to evaluate a plan, decision, or piece of work, lead with concrete failure scenarios and evidence, not affirmation.

## Evidence Before "Done"

- Claims of progress or completion point to evidence from this session: test output, grep/read results, or commands, cited with files and lines. Not verified — say so. Partial — say what is missing.
- Non-trivial changes need acceptance criteria in the project spec/progress file and targeted tests. Wire new modules into their caller in the same change. Record blockers separately from code failures.
- Auth, database transactions, realtime, payments, messaging, legal/privacy, or user-data work is not production-done without integration or smoke evidence. If the environment blocks that evidence, record the blocker.
- Frontend/UI changes: before claiming done, run targeted widget/app-flow tests and, when a runnable UI target exists, open the actual screen (emulator/browser) and check layout, states, and the happy path. Never done from code review or memory alone.

## Code Change Approval

- On an isolated worktree or branch, edit freely. Ask Zoe before: merging into the integration/main branch, database migrations, destructive or irreversible operations, and anything touching payments or user data in a deployed environment.
- When working directly on a shared branch with no isolation, ask before editing runtime-affecting code.
- Global agent-rule files may be edited when Zoe explicitly asks to update the rules.

## Architecture Boundaries

Use Clean Architecture unless the repo explicitly documents another pattern.

Dependency direction:

```text
ui -> application -> domain <- data
```

- `domain/` is pure models and business logic — no Flutter, Supabase, Drift, filesystem, network, or platform imports.
- UI never sees data-layer internals: no data-service/adapter/SDK imports, no raw rows, JSON maps, or SDK response objects. Row-to-model mapping lives in data mappers/repositories.
- Application code depends on repository/adapter abstractions with intention-revealing methods; controllers do not query Drift/Supabase/SQL directly.
- User-triggered or multi-step workflows go through command/use-case objects in `application/` — one intent, one `call()`/`execute()`, unit-testable with fakes. UI calls commands; it does not assemble workflows. Data adapters never call upward into application or UI.
- Entrypoints only initialize platform services and run the app. Seed/demo data belongs in data fakes or test fixtures. Route construction, share sheets, notifications, and plugin mechanics live in UI/platform adapters, not business controllers.
- Fake/demo adapters implement the same boundary as production adapters.
- If a requested change would violate these boundaries, refactor the boundary first.

## Scope

Don't add features, refactor, or introduce abstractions beyond what the task requires. Do the simplest thing that works well; avoid premature abstraction and half-finished implementations. Don't add error handling, fallbacks, or validation for scenarios that cannot happen — trust internal code and validate at system boundaries (user input, external APIs). Don't mix formatting churn or unrelated refactors with feature work.

## Privacy And Security

- Never expose raw GPS, personal data, auth tokens, or internal exceptions outside the minimum required boundary.
- Analytics, feed, and presence payloads must not include raw lat/lng.
- User identity must come from trusted auth/session state, not client-provided IDs.
- New endpoints or remote writes need authorization, input validation, abuse/rate consideration, and safe error messages.
- User-data tasks must answer retention, third-party sharing, disclosure, and deletion behavior before being called complete.

## Pull Requests

Based on Google eng-practices CL guidance plus standard PR-template conventions.

Title: imperative, specific, states the outcome — not the activity. "Make WindowsService test suite compile, run safely, and pass", never "Fix tests" / "Update code". Include the ticket key (e.g. MVP-XXXX) when one exists.

Description template (omit a section only when truly empty):

```markdown
## Summary
2-4 sentences: the problem first, then what this PR does about it.
Written for a reader with zero session context — it becomes permanent
history.

## Context
Ticket, related PRs, root-cause commits (short SHAs), design docs.
Why now, why this approach; known limitations.

## Changes
Bulleted, grouped by area. Separate production changes from test-only
changes explicitly. Call out anything non-obvious or behavior-affecting.

## Testing
Exact evidence: build/test commands and their results, before/after
comparisons, manual verification steps. State what was NOT tested and
any environment blockers.

## Risks
Backward compatibility, migrations, config, payload/protocol changes,
rollout concerns. Write "Low/None" with one line of justification
rather than omitting.
```

Rules:

- Explain the why, not just the what — vague summaries and missing motivation are the #1 review complaint.
- Reference evidence precisely (commit SHAs, file paths, test counts), not "various fixes".
- UI changes: attach screenshots/GIFs.
- Keep it scannable: bullets over prose walls; bold the load-bearing facts.
- Target the repo's integration branch (e.g. `dev`) unless the repo documents otherwise; enable close-source-branch on merge.

## Project Files

Prefer repo/task-specific rules over this global file when they are narrower and coherent.

For substantial work, create or update:

- `.spec/<ticket>/tasks.md`
- `.spec/<ticket>/audit.md`
- `.spec/<ticket>/ai-development-map.md`
- `.spec/<ticket>/adr-*.md` when there is a real architecture decision

If a repo has no agent rules, add a thin repo `AGENTS.md` with repo-specific commands and boundaries.

@RTK.md
